In this system a spring (with spring constant 'k') is connected in parallel with a dashpot (with viscosity $$\small\eta$$).




From the options below, select which graph correctly represents what would happen if the spring constant of the spring was doubled, but the dashpot unchanged (represented by the blue line).

generalfeedback.text:
The image above shows the correct answer to this question.

The same force has been applied, but the spring constant has been doubled. Therefore, the displacement defined by the equation (F/k) has been halved.

The slope will asymptotically move towards this new value of (F/k).

The initial gradient of the slope represents the rate of displacement of the system, and is defined by (F/$$\small\eta$$). As $$\small\eta$$ remains unchanged, so too does the initial gradient of the slope.
